// TEST: exec_match_bind_arm
// EXPECT: output "zero;n:42"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// A bare BINDING arm (`x => …`) after a literal arm (codegen-completeness P2).
// This is a *value*-switch match (literal + bind), so it stays on the proven
// `switch` fast-path on js/ts/go — it must NOT regress to the if-chain. It
// exercises two backend-specific defects the fast-path carried:
//
//   - Go binding-drop: `x => …` lowered to `default:` with the name DISCARDED,
//     and the body referenced an undefined `x` (`go build` error). Fixed by
//     binding the value-switch scrutinee into `__v` (`switch __v := s; __v`) and
//     emitting `x := __v; _ = x` in the bind arm.
//   - Python bare-binding ordering: a `case x:` is irrefutable; it must follow
//     the literal `case 0:` so the literal arm is still reachable (a leading
//     irrefutable arm is a 3.10 `SyntaxError`). The natural arm order already
//     satisfies this; the fixture pins it.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn label(n: Int) -> String {
  match n {
    0 => return "zero"
    x => return "n:${x}"
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("${label(0)};${label(42)}")
}
